{"title_page": "Crisis of Character", "text_new": "{{Infobox book\n| italic title   = \n| name           = Crisis of Character\n| image          = Crisis of Character Book Cover.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| author         = Gary J. Byrne with Grant M. Schmidt\n| audio_read_by  = \n| title_orig     = \n| orig_lang_code = \n| translator     = \n| illustrator    = \n| cover_artist   = \n| country        = United States\n| language       = English\n| series         = \n| release_number = \n| subject        = American government\n| genre          = Tell-all\n| set_in         = Washington, D.C.\n| published      = June 28, 2016\n| publisher      = [[Center Street (publisher)|Center Street]]\n| publisher2     = \n| pub_date       = \n| english_pub_date = \n| media_type     = hardcover\n| pages          = \n| awards         = \n| isbn           = 978-1-4555-6887-1\n| isbn_note      = \n| oclc           = \n| dewey          = \n| congress       = \n| followed_by    = \n| native_wikisource = \n| wikisource     = \n| notes          =\n| exclude_cover  = \n| website        = \n}}\n'''''Crisis of Character: A White House Secret Service Officer Discloses His Firsthand Experience with Hillary, Bill, and How They Operate ''''' is a best-selling 2016 book by former [[United States Secret Service Uniformed Division]] officer Gary J. Byrne with Grant M. Schmidt that purports to describe President [[Bill Clinton]] and First Lady [[Hillary Rodham Clinton]] as they resided in the [[White House]] during portions of the 1993\u20132001 [[Clinton administration]], alleging marital infidelities on his part and an imperious manner on hers.<ref name=\"Borchers\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/news/the-fix/wp/2016/06/29/this-clinton-tell-all-is-an-instant-best-seller-so-why-is-the-media-ignoring-it/|title=This Clinton tell-all is an instant best-seller. So why is the media 'ignoring' it?|work=[[The Washington Post]]|date=June 30, 2016|access-date=July 2, 2016|last=Borchers|first=Callum}}</ref><ref name=\"Dovere\">{{cite web|url=http://www.politico.com/story/2016/06/hillary-bill-clinton-secret-service-224578|title=Secret Service veterans denounce anti-Clinton tell-all book|work=[[Politico]]|date=June 21, 2016|access-date=July 2, 2016|last=Dovere|first=Edward-Isaac|authorlink=Edward-Isaac Dovere}}</ref> The book also portrays a volatile relationship between the First Couple.<ref name=\"fnc\">{{cite news|url=http://www.foxnews.com/politics/2016/06/05/secret-service-officers-book-details-clintons-crisis-character.html|title=Secret Service officer's book details Clintons' 'crisis of character'|date=June 5, 2016|work=Fox News|publisher=[[FOX News Network]]|access-date=July 2, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Publication ==\nThe book is published by [[Center Street (publisher)|Center Street]], an imprint of [[Hachette Book Group]]. Part of its commercial success was due to strong support from [[conservative media]].<ref name=\"Media Matters\">{{cite web|url=http://mediamatters.org/research/2016/06/29/gary-byrnes-anti-clinton-book-contradicted-his-own-testimony-and-he-cant-explain-it/211279|title=Gary Byrne's Anti-Clinton Book Is Contradicted By His Own Testimony, and He Can't Explain It|last=Vogel|first=Pam|date=June 29, 2016|publisher=[[Media Matters for America]]|access-date=July 3, 2016}}</ref> Advance excerpts were also published in newspapers such as the ''[[Boston Herald]]''.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.bostonherald.com/news/us_politics/2016/06/excerpts_from_crisis_of_confidence|title=Excerpts from 'Crisis of Confidence'|work=[[Boston Herald]]|date=June 22, 2016|access-date=July 3, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Content and themes ==\nIn addressing current affairs, in particular making reference to the [[Hillary Clinton presidential campaign, 2016]], in the context of which the book was published, Byrne concludes that from his experiences, Hillary Clinton \"lacks the integrity and temperament to serve in the office\".<ref name=\"fnc\" />  Like several other works published around this time, the book emphasizes Clinton's supposed predilection towards repetitively foul language.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2016/10/14/books/review-the-anti-clinton-brigades-four-letter-word-obsession.html|title=Review: The Anti-Clinton Brigade's Four-Letter Word Obsession|author=Jennifer Senior|date=October 13, 2016|work=The new York Times}}</ref>\n\nThe work also includes some episodes from the author's career that took place during prior presidential administrations.<ref name=\"fnc\" />\n\n== Responses ==\nThe nonpartisan Association of Former Agents of the United States Secret Service denounced the book for making \"security harder by eroding the trust between agents and the people they protect\".<ref name=\"Dovere\" /> Members of that Association also said that Byrne's job and role at that time would not have given him the level of access that many of the book's tales would be dependent upon.<ref name=\"Dovere\" /> Former members of the Secret Service suspect that Byrne was, as paraphrased by a reporter, \"working from office rumors that he's cinematically written himself into\".<ref name=\"Borchers\" /> [[Media Matters]] wrote that in places Byrnes' account in the book stood in contradiction to his sworn testimony before the Independent Counsel during the [[Lewinsky scandal]] in 1998.<ref name=\"Media Matters\" />\n\nAn opposite stance was taken by the author, party of interest [[Donald Trump]], and some in the conservative commentariat, who said that the mainstream media was deliberately ignoring the book.<ref name=\"Borchers\" /> Byrne's publicist declaimed, \"the Clintons always trash the messenger\".<ref name=\"Dovere\" />\n\n== Critical reception ==\nA review in the ''[[American Thinker]]'' proclaimed \"''Crisis of Character'' is the perfect name for a book about Hillary Clinton.\"<ref name=at>{{cite web|url=http://www.americanthinker.com/articles/2016/07/hillary_clintons_emcrisis_of_characterem.html|title=Hillary Clinton's ''Crisis of Character''|work=[[American Thinker]]|last=Cooper|first=Elise|date=July 15, 2016|access-date=August 10, 2016}}</ref>\nA review in ''[[The Washington Times]]'' stated that the book contained surprisingly little about Hillary Clinton and that what it did relate often was second-hand; instead, the review continued, the book was most valuable as a memoir by the agent and for his insights into the job and his life.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Eckert|first1=Fred J.|title=BOOK REVIEW: 'Crisis of Character'|url=http://www.washingtontimes.com/news/2016/jul/10/book-review-crisis-of-character-a-white-house-secr/|work=[[The Washington Times]]|access-date=August 1, 2016|date=July 10, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== Commercial reception ==\nThe book rose to number two on the [[Amazon.com|Amazon]] bestsellers list within a few days of its release.<ref name=\"Borchers\" />\n\nSoon after publication, the book debuted atop the [[The New York Times Non-Fiction Best Sellers of 2016|''New York Times'' Non-Fiction best seller list]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Books \u2013 Best Sellers \u2013 Hardcover Nonfiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/07/17/hardcover-nonfiction/|access-date=August 1, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=July 17, 2016}}</ref> and stayed on top during its second through fifth weeks.<ref>{{cite web|title=Books \u2013 Best Sellers \u2013 Hardcover Nonfiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/07/24/hardcover-nonfiction/|access-date=August 1, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=July 24, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Books \u2013 Best Sellers \u2013 Hardcover Nonfiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/07/31/hardcover-nonfiction/|access-date=August 1, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=July 31, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Books \u2013 Best Sellers \u2013 Hardcover Nonfiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/08/07/hardcover-nonfiction/|access-date=August 1, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=August 7, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Books \u2013 Best Sellers \u2013 Hardcover Nonfiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/08/14/hardcover-nonfiction/|access-date=August 10, 2016|work=The New York Times|date=August 14, 2016}}</ref> In its sixth week on the list it fell a couple of notches from its perch, followed by a couple spots' fall more the week following. The next two weeks were spent at number seven, followed by a placement at number ten on its tenth week on the list,<ref>{{cite web|title=Books \u2013 Best Sellers \u2013 Hardcover Nonfiction|url=https://www.nytimes.com/books/best-sellers/2016/09/18/hardcover-nonfiction/|work=The New York Times|date=September 18, 2016|access-date=January 11, 2016}}</ref> which was its final appearance on the official list.\n\nThe book also appeared as number one on the ''[[Publishers Weekly]]'' list.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.freep.com/story/entertainment/arts/2016/07/15/book-best-sellers-week-ending-july/87154516/|title=Best-selling books: 'Magic' and 'Crisis of Character'|work=[[Detroit Free Press]]|date=July 15, 2016|access-date=July 20, 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.hachettebookgroup.com/titles/gary-j-byrne/crisis-of-character/9781455568871/ Publisher's official site for book]\n\n[[Category:2016 non-fiction books]]\n[[Category:Books about Bill Clinton]]\n[[Category:Books about Hillary Clinton]]\n[[Category:Books about the Clinton administration]]\n[[Category:American political books]]\n[[Category:United States Secret Service]]\n[[Category:Literary collaborations]]\n[[Category:Center Street (publisher) books]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox book\n| italic title   = \n| name           = Crisis of Character\n| image          = Crisis of Character Book Cover.jpg\n| image_size     = \n| alt            = \n| caption        = \n| author         = Gary J. Byrne with Grant M. Schmidt\n| audio_read_by  = \n| title_orig