{"title_page": "Johan Velde van der Merwe", "text_new": "{{Infobox police officer|name=Johan Velde van der Merwe|birth_date=25 August 1936|honorific prefix=General|honorific suffix=[[Order of the Star of South Africa|SSAS]] [[South African Police Star for Outstanding Service|SOE]]|birth_place=Ermelo|country=South Africa|nationality=South African|status=Retired|serviceyears=1953-1995|rank=General}}\n\nGeneral '''Johan Velde van der Merwe''' (born 25 August 1936) is a South African police officer.{{sfn|TRC|1998}} He held senior positions in the Security Branch and was Commissioner of the [[South African Police]] from 1990 to 1995.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=115}}\n\n== Early life ==\nVan der Merwe was born in [[Ermelo, Mpumalanga|Ermelo]] in August 1936 to a family of conservative [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] supporters.{{sfn|TRC|1998}} He attended Ermelo High School and enjoyed sport.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=107}} After leaving school, Johan joined the [[South African Police]] in 1953.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=108}}\n\n== Career in the police ==\n\n=== Early career ===\n\nInterviewed after retirement, van der Merwe says that he enjoyed initial training.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=108}} In 1961 he was posted to [[Standerton]] in charge of administration of the new headquarters.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=108}} From 1963 to 1966 he worked in an administrative role at Security Headquarters.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=108-9}}\n\nFrom 1966 to 1970, he commanded a border post at the South Africa-[[Lesotho]] border.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=109}} When interviewed, he said that the Lesotho government under [[Leabua Jonathan]] enjoyed far less support than his superiors thought.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=109-10}}\n\nIn 1970, he was posted to the Security Branch in [[Bloemfontein]]; he eventually took command throughout the [[Orange Free State (Province)|Orange Free State]].{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=110}} Interviewed, he claimed to have helped to prevent unrest during the [[Soweto uprising]] in the Free State due to his close relations with parents of schoolchildren.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=111-2}}\n\nFrom 1979 he was then posted to [[South West Africa]],{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=112}} now [[Namibia]], which was then illegally under the control of the South African authorities.{{sfn|State Department|2009}} He recalled in an interview that he had \u201calmost unlimited legal powers\u201d in Namibia due to the co-operation of the Administrator General; recalling his time in Namibia, he said that he \u201cwould not [have] miss[ed it]\u2026for all the money in the world\u201d.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=115}}\n\n=== Time in the Security Branch and as Commissioner ===\n\nIn 1983 he was posted to Pretoria, where he rose initially from second in charge of the Security Branch to Head of Security, before becoming Deputy Commissioner and then in 1990 Commissioner of the [[South African Police]].{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=115}}\n\nIn 1985 he had a report sent to the minister requesting further powers, but was rebuked by [[Louis le Grange]], then Minister of Police.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=116}} In van der Merwe's view, the [[apartheid]] government's response to the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] (UDF) was hobbled by several factors: arrestees had the right to have the evidence against them furnished before the court, which would frequently identify informers, and it was very difficult to detain children who participated in the unrest.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=117}} He says that at that time \u201cthe main drive for us as a Security Branch [was] to protect our people\u201d and to maintain law and order.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=118}}\n\nDespite the handover of power from the [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] to a non-racial [[Government of National Unity (South Africa)|government of national unity]] under the provisions of an [[Interim Constitution (South Africa)|negotiated interim constitution]],{{sfn|SAHO|2004}} van der Merwe remained Commissioner until 1995.\n\n== Retirement and application for amnesty ==\n\nIn 1995 van der Merwe resigned from the police force.{{sfn|Staff Reporter|1995}} The ''[[Mail & Guardian]]'' reported that he was pressured to resign by the then Safety and Security Minister [[Sydney Mufamadi]] over accusations that he was obstructing investigations into other [[apartheid]]-era officers and alleged so-called [[Third Force (South Africa)|Third Force]] activity.{{sfn|Staff Reporter|1995}}\n\nWith several other security policemen, van der Merwe successfully applied for amnesty from the [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission (South Africa)|Truth and Reconciliation Commission]] for various offences.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=106}}\n\nHowever, in 2007, van der Merwe along with [[Adriaan Vlok]], an [[apartheid]]-era Minister of Law and Order, and several others was convicted of the murder of [[Frank Chikane]], an anti-[[apartheid]] priest, in 1989, and received a suspended prison sentence.{{sfn|McGreal|2007}}\n\nIn 2016 van der Merwe demanded that the then [[President of South Africa|president]] [[Jacob Zuma]], former president [[Thabo Mbeki]], and former senior [[African National Congress|ANC]] member [[Mac Maharaj]] should be charged for murder.{{sfn|Drum Digital|2016}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov.za/trc/amntrans/1998/98072031_pre_cosatu3.htm|title=Amnesty hearing of Johannes Velde van der Merwe day 3|last=TRC|first=|date=22 July 1998|website=Truth and Reconciliation Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200413111451/https://www.justice.gov.za/trc/amntrans/1998/98072031_pre_cosatu3.htm|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Foster|first=D.H.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/60636397|title=The theatre of violence : narratives of protagonists in the South African conflict|date=2005|publisher=HSRC Press|others=Haupt, Paul., De Beer, Mar\u00e9sa., Institute for Justice and Reconciliation (South Africa)|year=|isbn=0-7969-2095-8|location=Cape Town|pages=|oclc=60636397|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ho/time/pcw/98678.htm|title=The End of Apartheid|last=State Department|date=2009|work=Archive: Information released online prior to January 20, 2009|publisher=United States Department of State|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205233840/http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ho/time/pcw/98678.htm|archive-date=2009-02-05|access-date=5 February 2009|quote=South Africa had illegally occupied neighboring Namibia at the end of World War II, and since the mid-1970s, Pretoria had used it as a base to fight the communist party in Angola.|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite news|last=Staff Reporter|first=|url=https://mg.co.za/article/1995-01-20-meddling-sap-chief-forced-out/|title=Meddling SAP chief forced out|date=20 January 1995|work=Mail and Guardian|access-date=|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/article/south-african-government-national-unity-gnu-1994-1999|title=South African Government of National Unity (GNU) \u2013 1994 \u2013 1999|last=SAHO|first=|date=6 May 2014|website=South African Government of National Unity|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite news|last=McGreal|first=Chris|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/aug/18/southafrica.chrismcgreal|title=Apartheid-era minister guilty of attempted murder|date=2007-08-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite news|last=Drum Digital|first=|url=https://www.news24.com/Drum/Archive/mbeki-zuma-maharaj-must-be-charged-for-church-street-bombing-apartheid-police-general-20170728-2|title=Mbeki, Zuma, Maharaj must be charged for Church Street bombing - apartheid police general|date=20 May 2016|work=Drum (News24)|access-date=|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[South African Police]]\n* [[Apartheid]]\n* [[Petrus Johann Coetzee]], fellow Commissioner of the South African Police\n\n[[Category:South African people]]\n[[Category:Police officers]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox police officer|name=Johan Velde van der Merwe|birth_date=25 August 1936|honorific prefix=General|honorific suffix=[[Order of the Star of South Africa|SSAS]] [[South African Police Star for Outstanding Service|SOE]]|birth_place=Ermelo|country=South Africa|nationality=South African|status=Retired|serviceyears=1953-1995|rank=General}}\n\nGeneral '''Johan Velde van der Merwe''' (born 25 August 1936) is a South African police officer.{{sfn|TRC|1998}} He held senior positions in the Security Branch and was Commissioner of the [[South African Police]] from 1990 to 1995.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=115}}\n\n== Early life ==\nVan der Merwe was born in [[Ermelo, Mpumalanga|Ermelo]] in August 1936 to a family of conservative [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] supporters.{{sfn|TRC|1998}} He attended Ermelo High School and enjoyed sport.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=107}} After leaving school, Johan joined the [[South African Police]] in 1953.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=108}}\n\n== Career in the police ==\n\n=== Early career ===\n\nInterviewed after retirement, van der Merwe says that he enjoyed initial training.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=108}} In 1961 he was posted to [[Standerton]] in charge of administration of the new headquarters.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=108}} From 1963 to 1966 he worked in an administrative role at Security Headquarters.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=108-9}}\n\nFrom 1966 to 1970, he commanded a border post at the South Africa-[[Lesotho]] border.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=109}} When interviewed, he said that the Lesotho government under [[Leabua Jonathan]] enjoyed far less support than his superiors thought.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=109-10}}\n\nIn 1970, he was posted to the Security Branch in [[Bloemfontein]]; he eventually took command throughout the [[Orange Free State (Province)|Orange Free State]].{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=110}} Interviewed, he claimed to have helped to prevent unrest during the [[Soweto uprising]] in the Free State due to his close relations with parents of schoolchildren.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=111-2}}\n\nFrom 1979 he was then posted to [[South West Africa]]<nowiki>, now [[Namibia]],{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=112}} which was then illegally under the control of the South African authorities.</nowiki>{{sfn|State Department|2009}} He recalled in an interview that he had \u201calmost unlimited legal powers\u201d in Namibia due to the co-operation of the Administrator General; recalling his time in Namibia, he said that he \u201cwould not [have] miss[ed it]\u2026for all the money in the world\u201d.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=115}}\n\n=== Time in the Security Branch and as Commissioner ===\n\nIn 1983 he was posted to Pretoria, where he rose initially from second in charge of the Security Branch to Head of Security, before becoming Deputy Commissioner and then in 1990 Commissioner of the [[South African Police]].{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=115}}\n\nIn 1985 he had a report sent to the minister requesting further powers, but was rebuked by [[Louis le Grange]], then Minister of Police.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=116}} In van der Merwe's view, the [[apartheid]] government's response to the [[United Democratic Front (South Africa)|United Democratic Front]] (UDF) was hobbled by several factors: arrestees had the right to have the evidence against them furnished before the court, which would frequently identify informers, and it was very difficult to detain children who participated in the unrest.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=117}} He says that at that time \u201cthe main drive for us as a Security Branch [was] to protect our people\u201d and to maintain law and order.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=118}}\n\nDespite the handover of power from the [[National Party (South Africa)|National Party]] to a non-racial [[Government of National Unity (South Africa)|government of national unity]] under the provisions of an [[Interim Constitution (South Africa)|negotiated interim constitution]],{{sfn|SAHO|2004}} van der Merwe remained Commissioner until 1995.\n\n== Retirement and application for amnesty ==\n\nIn 1995 van der Merwe resigned from the police force.{{sfn|Staff Reporter|1995}} The ''[[Mail & Guardian]]'' reported that he was pressured to resign by the then Safety and Security Minister [[Sydney Mufamadi]] over accusations that he was obstructing investigations into other [[apartheid]]-era officers and alleged so-called [[Third Force (South Africa)|Third Force]] activity.{{sfn|Staff Reporter|1995}}\n\nWith several other security policemen, van der Merwe successfully applied for amnesty from the [[Truth and Reconciliation Commission (South Africa)|Truth and Reconciliation Commission]] for various offences.{{sfn|Foster|2005|p=106}}\n\nHowever, in 2007, van der Merwe along with [[Adriaan Vlok]], an [[apartheid]]-era Minister of Law and Order, and several others was convicted of the murder of [[Frank Chikane]], an anti-[[apartheid]] priest, in 1989, and received a suspended prison sentence.{{sfn|McGreal|2007}}\n\nIn 2016 van der Merwe demanded that the then [[President of South Africa|president]] [[Jacob Zuma]], former president [[Thabo Mbeki]], and former senior [[African National Congress|ANC]] member [[Mac Maharaj]] should be charged for murder.{{sfn|Drum Digital|2016}}\n\n== Notes ==\n{{notelist}}\n{{reflist}}\n\n== References ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{Cite web|url=https://www.justice.gov.za/trc/amntrans/1998/98072031_pre_cosatu3.htm|title=Amnesty hearing of Johannes Velde van der Merwe day 3|last=TRC|first=|date=22 July 1998|website=Truth and Reconciliation Commission|url-status=live|archive-url=http://web.archive.org/web/20200413111451/https://www.justice.gov.za/trc/amntrans/1998/98072031_pre_cosatu3.htm|archive-date=12 April 2020|access-date=|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite book|last=Foster|first=D.H.|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/60636397|title=The theatre of violence : narratives of protagonists in the South African conflict|date=2005|publisher=HSRC Press|others=Haupt, Paul., De Beer, Mar\u00e9sa., Institute for Justice and Reconciliation (South Africa)|year=|isbn=0-7969-2095-8|location=Cape Town|pages=|oclc=60636397|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ho/time/pcw/98678.htm|title=The End of Apartheid|last=State Department|date=2009|work=Archive: Information released online prior to January 20, 2009|publisher=United States Department of State|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090205233840/http://2001-2009.state.gov/r/pa/ho/time/pcw/98678.htm|archive-date=2009-02-05|access-date=5 February 2009|quote=South Africa had illegally occupied neighboring Namibia at the end of World War II, and since the mid-1970s, Pretoria had used it as a base to fight the communist party in Angola.|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite news|last=Staff Reporter|first=|url=https://mg.co.za/article/1995-01-20-meddling-sap-chief-forced-out/|title=Meddling SAP chief forced out|date=20 January 1995|work=Mail and Guardian|access-date=|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite web|url=https://www.sahistory.org.za/article/south-african-government-national-unity-gnu-1994-1999|title=South African Government of National Unity (GNU) \u2013 1994 \u2013 1999|last=SAHO|first=|date=6 May 2014|website=South African Government of National Unity|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=|ref=harv}}\n* {{Cite news|last=McGreal|first=Chris|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2007/aug/18/southafrica.chrismcgreal|title=Apartheid-era minister guilty of attempted murder|date=2007-08-17|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-04-13|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|ref=harv}}\n*{{Cite news|last=Drum Digital|first=|url=https://www.news24.com/Drum/Archive/mbeki-zuma-maharaj-must-be-charged-for-church-street-bombing-apartheid-police-general-20170728-2|title=Mbeki, Zuma, Maharaj must be charged for Church Street bombing - apartheid police general|date=20 May 2016|work=Drum (News24)|access-date=|url-status=live|ref=harv}}\n{{refend}}\n\n== See also ==\n* [[South African Police]]\n* [[Apartheid]]\n* [[Petrus Johann Coetzee]], fellow Commissioner of the South African Police\n\n[[Category:South African people]]\n[[Category:Police officers]]\n[[Category:1936 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "Docentation", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer in the police:removed nowiki that cocked up sfn", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Johan_Velde_van_der_Merwe"}
{"title_page": "Mary Beth Cahill", "text_new": "{{short description|American political figure|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Mary Beth Cahill\n|office      = [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|Director of the Office of Public Liaison]]\n|president   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n|term_start  = February 5, 1999\n|term_end    = January 20, 2001\n|predecessor = [[Minyon Moore]]\n|successor   = [[Lezlee Westine]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1954|12}}\n|birth_place = [[Dorchester, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = Steve Champlin\n|education   = [[Emmanuel College (Massachusetts)|Emmanuel College, Massachusetts]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}\n}}\n'''Mary Beth Cahill''' (born December 1954) is an American [[political figure]] who served as the [[campaign manager]] of [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John Kerry]]'s [[election campaign|campaign]] for the [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] nomination for [[President of the United States|President]]. She was Kerry's second campaign manager; she replaced [[Jim Jordan (United States politics)|Jim Jordan]] in November 2003, after Jordan was fired by Kerry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/10/politics/09kerry.html?hp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045301/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/10/politics/09kerry.html?hp|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-04|publisher=[[New York Times]]|author=[[Associated Press]]|date=2003-11-10|accessdate=2009-07-28 | title=Kerry Fires Campaign Manager}} </ref> In February 2018, Cahill was named interim CEO of the [[Democratic National Committee]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debenedetti|first1=Gabriel|last2=Dovere|first2=Edward-Isaac|authorlink=Edward-Isaac Dovere|title=DNC hires Mary Beth Cahill as interim CEO|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/02/01/dnc-mary-beth-cahill-ceo-384342|accessdate=2 February 2018|publisher=Politico|date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nCahill was born in [[Dorchester, Massachusetts]] and raised in [[Framingham, Massachusetts]] by a large, politically active, [[Irish-Catholic]] family. Cahill graduated from [[Emmanuel College, Boston]], a small local Catholic liberal arts school with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[English studies|English]] and [[political science]] in 1976.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/jan/29/nation/na-cahill29|title=Campaign Manager in Spotlight as Kerry Becomes Frontrunner|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Johanna Neuman|date=2004-01-29|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://library.emmanuel.edu/ARCHIVE/sites/default/files/Emmanuel_Mag_Winter_Spring2003o.pdf|title=Years of Planning..|last=|first=|date=|work=Emmanuel magazine|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://gspm.gwu.edu/mary-beth-cahill|title=Mary Beth Cahill|last=|first=|date=|work=The Graduate School of Political Management|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCahill started her political career by working as a receptionist and caseworker for Congressman [[Robert Drinan]], a [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] priest. After which she became Chief of Staff for Representative [[Barney Frank]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://atlasproject.net/about-us/our-advisory-board/|title=Our Advisory Board|last=|first=|date=|work=atlasproject.net|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref> In 1986, she was the campaign manager for Senator [[Patrick Leahy]] (D-VT).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,596066,00.html|title=The Miracle Worker|author=[[Karen Tumulty]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=2004-03-08|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> She was also an Assistant to the President and [[White House Office of Public Liaison|Director of Public Liaison]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://whitehousetransitionproject.org/resources/briefing/WHTP-2009-03-Public%20Liaison.pdf |title=White House Transition Project Institutional Memory Series: The White House Office of Public Liaison |accessdate=2009-07-25 |page=8 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728174855/http://whitehousetransitionproject.org/resources/briefing/WHTP-2009-03-Public%20Liaison.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-28 }}</ref> in [[Bill Clinton]]'s White House and [[Chief of staff (United States Congress)|chief of staff]] to Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] (D-MA).\n\nFollowing the Kerry campaign, Cahill was a fellow at the [[Harvard Institute of Politics]] at [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] in the spring of 2005. She led a study group for undergraduates entitled \"Campaigns 101.\"\n\nCahill last worked to raise funds for Massachusetts Democratic gubernatorial candidate [[Deval Patrick]], who defeated Attorney General [[Thomas Reilly|Tom Reilly]] and businessman [[Chris Gabrieli]] in the [[Massachusetts gubernatorial election, 2006|2006 primary]] and [[Kerry Healey]] in the general election.\n\nCahill was the Executive Director of [[EMILY's List]] for five years and has trained women on how to run for political office in countries including [[Russia]], [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]], and [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n== Further reading ==\n* Garance Franke-Ruta, \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20051028001457/http://www.prospect.org/print/V15/4/franke-ruta-g.html Kerry's Women],\" ''[[The American Prospect]]'', April 1, 2004.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1812400|name=Mary Beth Cahill}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Mary Cahill}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Minyon Moore]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|Director of the Office of Public Liaison]]|years=1999\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lezlee Westine]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{WHOPL|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cahill, Mary Beth}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:American campaign managers]]\n[[Category:American political consultants]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Emmanuel College (Massachusetts) alumni]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government people]]\n[[Category:John Kerry]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Dorchester, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Framingham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:United States presidential advisors]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American political figure|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n|name        = Mary Beth Cahill\n|office      = [[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|Director of the Office of Public Liaison]]\n|president   = [[Bill Clinton]]\n|term_start  = February 5, 1999\n|term_end    = January 20, 2001\n|predecessor = [[Minyon Moore]]\n|successor   = [[Lezlee Westine]]\n|birth_date  = {{birth year and age|1954|12}}\n|birth_place = [[Dorchester, Massachusetts]], U.S.\n|death_date  = \n|death_place = \n|party       = [[Democratic Party (United States)|Democratic]]\n|spouse      = Steve Champlin\n|education   = [[Emmanuel College (Massachusetts)|Emmanuel College, Massachusetts]] {{small|([[Bachelor of Arts|BA]])}}\n}}\n'''Mary Beth Cahill''' (born December 1954) is an American [[political figure]] who served as the [[campaign manager]] of [[United States Senate|Senator]] [[John Kerry]]'s [[election campaign|campaign]] for the [[Democratic Party (US)|Democratic]] nomination for [[President of the United States|President]]. She was Kerry's second campaign manager; she replaced [[Jim Jordan (United States politics)|Jim Jordan]] in November 2003, after Jordan was fired by Kerry.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/10/politics/09kerry.html?hp|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304045301/http://www.nytimes.com/2003/11/10/politics/09kerry.html?hp|url-status=dead|archive-date=2016-03-04|publisher=[[New York Times]]|author=[[Associated Press]]|date=2003-11-10|accessdate=2009-07-28 | title=Kerry Fires Campaign Manager}} </ref> In February 2018, Cahill was named interim CEO of the [[Democratic National Committee]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Debenedetti|first1=Gabriel|last2=Dovere|first2=Edward-Isaac|title=DNC hires Mary Beth Cahill as interim CEO|url=https://www.politico.com/story/2018/02/01/dnc-mary-beth-cahill-ceo-384342|accessdate=2 February 2018|publisher=Politico|date=February 1, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nCahill was born in [[Dorchester, Massachusetts]] and raised in [[Framingham, Massachusetts]] by a large, politically active, [[Irish-Catholic]] family. Cahill graduated from [[Emmanuel College, Boston]], a small local Catholic liberal arts school with a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree in [[English studies|English]] and [[political science]] in 1976.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/2004/jan/29/nation/na-cahill29|title=Campaign Manager in Spotlight as Kerry Becomes Frontrunner|newspaper=[[Los Angeles Times]]|author=Johanna Neuman|date=2004-01-29|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://library.emmanuel.edu/ARCHIVE/sites/default/files/Emmanuel_Mag_Winter_Spring2003o.pdf|title=Years of Planning..|last=|first=|date=|work=Emmanuel magazine|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://gspm.gwu.edu/mary-beth-cahill|title=Mary Beth Cahill|last=|first=|date=|work=The Graduate School of Political Management|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nCahill started her political career by working as a receptionist and caseworker for Congressman [[Robert Drinan]], a [[Society of Jesus|Jesuit]] priest. After which she became Chief of Staff for Representative [[Barney Frank]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://atlasproject.net/about-us/our-advisory-board/|title=Our Advisory Board|last=|first=|date=|work=atlasproject.net|access-date=2018-11-22}}</ref> In 1986, she was the campaign manager for Senator [[Patrick Leahy]] (D-VT).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.time.com/time/magazine/article/0,9171,596066,00.html|title=The Miracle Worker|author=[[Karen Tumulty]]|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=2004-03-08|accessdate=2009-07-28}}</ref> She was also an Assistant to the President and [[White House Office of Public Liaison|Director of Public Liaison]]<ref>{{cite news|url=http://whitehousetransitionproject.org/resources/briefing/WHTP-2009-03-Public%20Liaison.pdf |title=White House Transition Project Institutional Memory Series: The White House Office of Public Liaison |accessdate=2009-07-25 |page=8 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110728174855/http://whitehousetransitionproject.org/resources/briefing/WHTP-2009-03-Public%20Liaison.pdf |archivedate=2011-07-28 }}</ref> in [[Bill Clinton]]'s White House and [[Chief of staff (United States Congress)|chief of staff]] to Senator [[Ted Kennedy]] (D-MA).\n\nFollowing the Kerry campaign, Cahill was a fellow at the [[Harvard Institute of Politics]] at [[Harvard University]]'s [[John F. Kennedy School of Government]] in the spring of 2005. She led a study group for undergraduates entitled \"Campaigns 101.\"\n\nCahill last worked to raise funds for Massachusetts Democratic gubernatorial candidate [[Deval Patrick]], who defeated Attorney General [[Thomas Reilly|Tom Reilly]] and businessman [[Chris Gabrieli]] in the [[Massachusetts gubernatorial election, 2006|2006 primary]] and [[Kerry Healey]] in the general election.\n\nCahill was the Executive Director of [[EMILY's List]] for five years and has trained women on how to run for political office in countries including [[Russia]], [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]], and [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n== Further reading ==\n* Garance Franke-Ruta, \"[https://web.archive.org/web/20051028001457/http://www.prospect.org/print/V15/4/franke-ruta-g.html Kerry's Women],\" ''[[The American Prospect]]'', April 1, 2004.\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|id=1812400|name=Mary Beth Cahill}}\n*{{C-SPAN|Mary Cahill}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-off}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Minyon Moore]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[White House Office of Public Engagement and Intergovernmental Affairs|Director of the Office of Public Liaison]]|years=1999\u20132001}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[Lezlee Westine]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{WHOPL|state=collapsed}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cahill, Mary Beth}}\n[[Category:1954 births]]\n[[Category:American campaign managers]]\n[[Category:American political consultants]]\n[[Category:American people of Irish descent]]\n[[Category:Emmanuel College (Massachusetts) alumni]]\n[[Category:John F. Kennedy School of Government people]]\n[[Category:John Kerry]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Massachusetts Democrats]]\n[[Category:People from Dorchester, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:People from Framingham, Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:United States presidential advisors]]\n", "name_user": "Patapsco913", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mary_Beth_Cahill"}
{"title_page": "General knowledge", "text_new": "{{Distinguish|Common knowledge}}\n{{Too few opinions|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:G\u00f6ttingen-SUB-Encyclopedia.Americana.JPG|thumb|An [[encyclopedia]] is a repository of general knowledge]]\n\n'''General knowledge''' is information that has been accumulated over time through various mediums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dictionary.cambridge.org/us/dictionary/english/general-knowledge|title=GENERAL KNOWLEDGE|website=Cambridge English Dictionary|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> It excludes specialized learning that can only be obtained with extensive training and information confined to a single medium. General knowledge is an essential component of [[crystallized intelligence]]. It is strongly associated with [[G factor (psychometrics)|general intelligence]] and with [[openness to experience]].<ref>T. C. Bates and A. Shieles. (2003). Crystallized Intelligence is a product of Speed and Drive for Experience: The Relationship of Inspection Time and Openness to g and Gc. ''Intelligence'', '''31''', [https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/S0160-2896(02)00176-9 275-287]</ref>\n\nStudies have found that people who are highly knowledgeable in a particular domain tend to be knowledgeable in many.<ref name=\"rolfhus&ackerman\">{{cite journal|last=Rolfhus|first=Eric L.|author2=Ackerman, Phillip L.|year=1999|title=Assessing individual differences in knowledge: Knowledge, intelligence, and related traits|url=http://internal.psychology.illinois.edu/~broberts/Rolfhus%20&%20Ackerman,%201999.pdf|journal=Journal of Educational Psychology|volume=91|issue=3|pages=511\u2013526|doi=10.1037/0022-0663.91.3.511|access-date=2019-12-25|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120415101812/http://internal.psychology.illinois.edu/~broberts/Rolfhus%20%26%20Ackerman%2C%201999.pdf|archive-date=2012-04-15|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"ackerman2001\">{{cite journal|last1=Ackerman|first1=Phillip L.|last2=Bowen|first2=Kristy R.|last3=Beier|first3=Margaret E.|last4=Kanfer|first4=Ruth|year=2001|title=Determinants of individual differences and gender differences in knowledge|url=http://www.mendeley.com/research/determinants-individual-differences-gender-differences-knowledge-5/|journal=Journal of Educational Psychology|volume=93|issue=4|pages=797\u2013825|doi=10.1037/0022-0663.93.4.797}}</ref> General knowledge is thought to be supported by long-term [[semantic memory]] ability.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Smith|first=Amy M.|last2=Hughes|first2=Gregory I.|last3=Davis|first3=F. Caroline|last4=Thomas|first4=Ayanna K.|date=March 2019|title=Acute stress enhances general-knowledge semantic memory|journal=Hormones and Behavior|language=en|volume=109|pages=38\u201343|doi=10.1016/j.yhbeh.2019.02.003}}</ref> General knowledge also supports [[Schema (psychology)|schemata]] for textual understanding.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=An|first=Shuying|date=2013-01-01|title=Schema Theory in Reading|url=https://pdfs.semanticscholar.org/8df7/b09d082e889ffe3b724c780562e097262c42.pdf|journal=Theory and Practice in Language Studies|volume=3|issue=1|pages=|doi=10.4304/tpls.3.1.130-134|issn=1799-2591|via=}}</ref> In 2019, it was found in a survey that [[New Zealand]]ers had \"concerning\" gaps in their general knowledge.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kiwis display knowledge gaps in areas like basic maths, geography, and New Zealand and world history|url=https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/117503130/basic-knowledge-gaps-exposed-in-new-zealand-initiative-survey-of-kiwis-general-knowledge|first=Damian|last=George|date=November 19, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Individual differences==\n\n===Intelligence===\nHigh scorers on tests of general knowledge tend to also score highly on intelligence tests. [[IQ]] has been found to robustly predict general knowledge scores even after accounting for differences in age, sex, and [[five factor model]] personality traits.<ref name=Furnham2006 /><ref name=chamorro /><ref name=Furnham2008>{{cite journal|last=Furnham|first=Adrian |author2=Swami, Viren |author3=Arteche, Adriane |author4-link=Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic |author4=Chamorro-Premuzic, Tomas|title=Cognitive ability, learning approaches and personality correlates of general knowledge|journal=Educational Psychology|year=2008|volume=28|pages=427\u2013437|doi=10.1080/01443410701727376|issue=4}}</ref> However, many general knowledge tests are designed to create a normal distribution of answers, creating a [[Normal distribution|bell shaped curve]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.psychologytoday.com/blog/the-gift-aging/201404/what-constitutes-general-knowledge|title=What Constitutes General Knowledge?|last=Stuart-Hamilton|first=Ian|date=6 April 2014|website=Psychology Today|language=en-US|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref>\n\nGeneral knowledge is also moderately associated with verbal ability, though only weakly or not at all with numerical and spatial ability.<ref name=\"rolfhus&ackerman\" /> As with crystallized intelligence, general knowledge has been found to increase with age.<ref name=Furnham2007>{{cite journal|last=Furnham|first=Adrian|last2=Christopher|first2=Andrew N.|last3=Garwood|first3=Jeanette|last4=Martin|first4=G. Neil|title=Approaches to learning and the acquisition of general knowledge|journal=Personality and Individual Differences|year=2007|volume=43|pages=1563\u20131571|doi=10.1016/j.paid.2007.04.013|issue=6}}</ref>\n\n===Long-term semantic memory===\nGeneral knowledge is stored as [[semantic memory]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Citation|last=Glisky|first=Elizabeth L.|title=Changes in Cognitive Function in Human Aging|date=2007|url=http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK3885/|work=Brain Aging: Models, Methods, and Mechanisms|editor-last=Riddle|editor-first=David R.|series=Frontiers in Neuroscience|publisher=CRC Press/Taylor & Francis|isbn=9780849338182|pmid=21204355|access-date=2019-08-24}}</ref> Most semantic memory is preserved through old age, though there are deficits in retrieval of certain specific words correlated with aging.<ref name=\":0\" /> In addition, [[Stress (biology)|stress]] or various emotional levels can negatively affect semantic memory retrieval.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n===Personality===\nPeople high in general knowledge<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitknowledge.com/|title=Knowledge For All}}</ref> tend to be highly [[openness to experience|open to new experiences]]<ref name=Furnham2006>{{cite journal|last=Furnham|first=Adrian|author2=Chamorro-Premuzic, Tomas |authorlink2=Tomas Chamorro-Premuzic |title=Personality, intelligence, and general knowledge|journal=Learning and Individual Differences|year=2006|volume=16|pages=79\u201390|url=http://www.mendeley.com/research/personality-intelligence-general-knowledge/|doi=10.1016/j.lindif.2005.07.002}}</ref><ref name=chamorro>{{cite journal|last=Chamorro-Premuzic|first=Tomas|author2=Furnham, Adrian|author3=Ackerman, Phillip L.|title=Ability and personality correlates of general knowledge|journal=Personality and Individual Differences|year=2006|volume=41|pages=419\u2013429|url=http://jupiter.gold.ac.uk/media/ChamorroPremuzicFunrhamAckerman2006PAID.pdf|doi=10.1016/j.paid.2005.11.036|issue=3|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426065554/http://jupiter.gold.ac.uk/media/ChamorroPremuzicFunrhamAckerman2006PAID.pdf|archivedate=2012-04-26}}</ref><ref name=Furnham2008 /><ref name=Furnham2007 /> and in [[typical intellectual engagement]].<ref name=chamorro /><ref name=Furnham2008 /> The relationship between openness to experience and general knowledge remains robust even when IQ is taken into account.<ref name=Furnham2006 /><ref name=Furnham2008 /> People high in openness may be more motivated to engage in intellectual pursuits that increase their knowledge.<ref name=Furnham2008 /> Relationships between general knowledge and other [[five factor model]] traits tend to be weak and inconsistent. Though one study found that [[extraversion]] and [[neuroticism]] were negatively [[correlation and dependence|correlated]] with general knowledge,<ref name=chamorro /> others found that they were unrelated.<ref name=Furnham2006 /><ref name=Furnham2007 /> Inconsistent results have also been found for [[conscientiousness]].{{refn|[[Adrian Furnham|Furnham]] et al.<ref name=Furnham2006 /> found positive correlations with general knowledge in his first and third studies, but no significant relationship in his second. Studies by others have found no significant relationship.<ref name=chamorro /><ref name=Furnham2007 />|group=note}}\n\n==Predictor of achievement==\nA number of studies have assessed whether performance on a general knowledge test can predict achievement in particular areas, namely in academics,<ref name=Furnham2009>\n{{Cite journal\n | first = Adrian\n | last = Furnham\n |last2 =Monsen\n |first2 =J. & Ahmetoglu\n | year = 2009\n | title = Typical intellectual engagement, Big Five personality traits, approaches to learning and cognitive ability predictors of academic performance | quote =\n | journal = British Journal of Educational Psychology\n | volume = 79\n | issue = 4\n | pages = 769\u2013782\n | pmid=19245744\n | doi = 10.1348/978185409X412147}}\n</ref> proofreading,<ref name=proofreading>\n{{Cite journal\n | first = Adrian\n | last = Furnham\n | year = 2010\n | title = Proofreading as an index of crystallised intelligence\n | journal = Educational Psychology\n | volume = 30\n | issue = 6\n | pages = 735\u2013754\n | doi=10.1080/01443410.2010.506005}}</ref> and creativity.<ref name=creativity>\n{{Cite journal\n | first = Mark\n | last = Batey |author2=Furnham, Adrian |author3=Safiullina, Xeniya\n | year = 2010\n | title = Intelligence, general knowledge and personality as predictors of creativity\n | journal = Learning and Individual Differences\n | volume = 20\n | issue = 5\n | pages = 532\u2013535\n | doi=10.1016/j.lindif.2010.04.008}}\n</ref>\n\n===Academic achievement===\nGeneral knowledge has been found to predict exam results in a study of British schoolchildren.<ref name=Furnham2009 /> The study examined cognitive ability and personality predictors of exam performance and found that general knowledge was positively correlated with [[GCSE]] English, mathematics, and overall exam results. General knowledge test scores predicted exam results, even after controlling for IQ, five factor model personality traits, and learning styles.\n\n===Proofreading===\nGeneral knowledge has been found to robustly predict proofreading skills in university students.<ref name=proofreading/> A study found that proofreading had a larger correlation with general knowledge than with general intelligence, verbal reasoning, or openness to experience. In a [[multiple regression|multiple regression analysis]] using general knowledge, general intelligence, verbal reasoning, five factor personality traits, and learning styles as predictors, only general knowledge was a significant predictor.\n\n===Creativity===\nGeneral knowledge has been found to have weak associations with measures of creativity.<ref name=creativity/> In a study examining contributions of personality and intelligence to creativity, general knowledge was positively correlated with tests of [[divergent thinking]], but was unrelated to a biographical measure of creative achievement, self-rated creativity, or a composite measure of creativity. The relationship between general knowledge and divergent thinking became non-significant when controlling for fluid intelligence.\n\n==Game shows and quizzes==\nMany [[game shows]] use general knowledge questions. Game shows such as ''[[Who Wants to Be a Millionaire?]]'' and ''[[Fifteen to One]]'' centre their questions on general knowledge, while others shows focus questions more on specific subjects. Some shows ask questions both on specific subjects and on general knowledge, including ''[[Eggheads (TV series)|Eggheads]]'' and ''[[Mastermind (TV series)|''Mastermind'']]''. In ''Mastermind'', contestants choose their own \"specialist subject\" before answering general knowledge questions, whereas in ''Eggheads'' the subjects are chosen at random.\n[[File:Trivialpursuit Token.jpg|thumb|Questions drawn from the game [[Trivial Pursuit]] have been utilised in a number of psychological experiments concerning general knowledge.<ref>{{cite journal|last=Dijksterhuis |first=A. |author2=van Knippenberg, A. |title=The relation between perception and behavior, or how to win a game of trivial pursuit |journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology |year=1998 |volume=74 |issue=4 |pages=865\u201377 |pmid=9569649 |url=http://www.biz.colostate.edu/MPPCWorkshop/Documents/Readings/Campbell/Campbell_DijksterhuisVanKnippenbergJPSP1998.pdf |doi=10.1037/0022-3514.74.4.865 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100614042321/http://www.biz.colostate.edu/MPPCWorkshop/Documents/Readings/Campbell/Campbell_DijksterhuisVanKnippenbergJPSP1998.pdf |archivedate=2010-06-14 }}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last=Dijksterhuis|first=A.|title=Seeing one thing and doing another: Contrast effects in automatic behavior|journal=Journal of Personality and Social Psychology|date=October 1998|volume=75|issue=4|pages=862\u2013871|doi=10.1037/0022-3514.75.4.862}}</ref>]]\n\n==See also==\n* [[IQ]]\n* [[Intelligence]]\n* [[High culture]]\n* [[Cattell-Horn-Carroll theory]]\n* [[Cultural literacy]]\n* [[Core knowledge foundation]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist|group=note}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n<!--======================== {{No more links}} ============================\n                        | PLEASE BE CAUTIOUS IN ADDING MORE LINKS TO THIS ARTICLE. Wikipedia  |\n                        | is not a collection of links nor should it be used for advertising. |\n                        |                                                                     |\n                        |           Excessive or inappropriate links WILL BE DELETED.         |\n                        | See [[Wikipedia:External links]] & [[Wikipedia:Spam]] 